âœ… Jenkins User Management using LDAP / LDAPS (Correct Explanation)
ğŸ”¹ What is LDAPS?

LDAP over SSL/TLS
Secure authentication using certificates
Uses port 636
Preferred over plain LDAP (389)

âŒ Important correction (VERY IMPORTANT)

ğŸ‘‰ You do NOT create base.ldif, users.ldif, groups.ldif on Jenkins

Those LDIF files are created on the LDAP server, NOT Jenkins.
They are used to:
Create users
Create groups
Define relationships (user â†” group)

Examples:

users.ldif â†’ user entries
groups.ldif â†’ group entries
base.ldif â†’ base DN structure

âœ”ï¸ This is LDAP admin work, not Jenkins work.

ğŸŸ¢ Correct Jenkins-side configuration steps
1ï¸âƒ£ Configure LDAP / LDAPS in Jenkins

Go to:

Manage Jenkins â†’ Security â†’ Configure Global Security

Under Security Realm:

Select LDAP
Enable Use SSL (LDAPS)

2ï¸âƒ£ Provide LDAP details

You configure:

LDAP server IP / hostname
Port: 636
Root DN
dc=example,dc=com


User search base:
ou=users
Group search base:
ou=groups

LDAP bind DN (service account)

LDAP bind password
Upload / trust LDAP SSL certificate (via JVM keystore)

3ï¸âƒ£ Test LDAP connection

âœ”ï¸ Jenkins provides Test LDAP Settings
Always mention this in interviews.

4ï¸âƒ£ Configure Authorization (Permissions)

Go to Authorization section:
Common options:
Matrix-based security
Role-based authorization strategy (recommended)

5ï¸âƒ£ Assign permissions to LDAP users/groups

Example permissions:
Overall â†’ Read
Job â†’ Build
Job â†’ Read
Job â†’ View
Job â†’ Workspace
View â†’ Read
Logs â†’ View

ğŸ‘‰ Permissions are mapped to LDAP groups, not individual users (best practice).

ğŸŸ¢ Interview-ready corrected answer (Short & Perfect)

â€œJenkins user management is done using LDAP or LDAPS. User and group creation is handled on the LDAP server using LDIF files. In Jenkins, we configure LDAP under Global Security, enable LDAPS for secure 
authentication, provide LDAP server details, and then use matrix or role-based authorization to assign permissions to LDAP groups.

